|| {{IPA|\u02c8t(j)u\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| Vespa || vesper || {{IPA|\u02c8v\u025bsp\u0259}}\n|-\n| via || veer || {{IPA|\u02c8v\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| Wanda || wander || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u0252nd\u0259}}\n|-\n| Weston || western || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u025bst\u0259n}}\n|-\n| [[Wicca]] || wicker || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u026ak\u0259}}\n|}\n\n=== Father\u2013farther merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>PALM</small> and <small>START</small>. It is found in the speech of the great majority of non-rhotic speakers, including those of England, Wales, the United States, the Caribbean, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa. It may be absent in some non-rhotic speakers in the Bahamas.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| ah || are || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| ah || (h)our || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0}} || With [[monophthongization|smoothing]].\n|-\n| ah || R; ar || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| alms || arms || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0mz}}\n|-\n| alms || harms || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0mz}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| Ana || [[Arne (name)|Arne]] || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| balmy || barmy || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0mi}}\n|-\n| calmer || karma || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Chalmers (surname)|Chalmers]] || charmers || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283\u0251\u02d0m\u0259z}}\n|-\n| [[Dahmer (disambiguation)|Dahmer]] || dharma || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| Dhaka || darker || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0k\u0259}} || With trap\u2013bath split.\n|-\n| fa || far || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| father || farther || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0\u00f0\u0259}}\n|-\n| Ghana || Garner || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Hamm]] || harm || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0251\u02d0m}} || With trap\u2013bath split.\n|-\n| [[Jahn]] || yarn || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0251\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| kava || carver || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0v\u0259}}\n|-\n| lava || larva || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0251\u02d0v\u0259}}\n|-\n| ma || mar || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| pa || par || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| Palma || [[Parma]] || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| palmer; Palmer || [[Parma]] || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| ska || scar || {{IPA|\u02c8sk\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| spa || spar || {{IPA|\u02c8sp\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| Stata || starter || {{IPA|\u02c8st\u0251\u02d0t\u0259}} \n|}\n\n=== Pawn\u2013porn merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>THOUGHT</small> and <small>NORTH</small>. It is found in most of the same accents as the ''father\u2013farther'' merger described above, but is absent from the Bahamas and Guyana.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| alk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| auk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| aw || or || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awe || or || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| balk || bork || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| bawn || born || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| caulk || cork || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| cawed || chord || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| cawed || cord || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| draw || drawer || {{IPA|\u02c8dr\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| gnaw || nor || {{IPA|\u02c8n\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| hawk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| laud || lord || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| lawed || lord || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| lawn || lorn || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| pawn || porn || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| sought || sort || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| stalk || stork || {{IPA|\u02c8st\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| talk || torque || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| taught || tort || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| taut || tort || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| taw || tor || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| thaw || [[Thor]] || {{IPA|\u02c8\u03b8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n=== Caught\u2013court merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>THOUGHT</small> and <small>FORCE</small>. It is found in those non-rhotic accents containing the ''pawn''\u2013''porn'' merger that have also undergone the [[horse\u2013hoarse merger]]. These include the accents of Southern England, Wales, non-rhotic New York City speakers, Trinidad and the Southern hemisphere. In such accents a three-way merger ''awe''-''or''-''ore/oar'' results.  However, Labov et al. suggest that, in New York City English, this merger is present in perception not production.  As in, although even locals perceive themselves using the same vowel in both cases, they tend to produce the {{sc2|FORCE}} higher and more retracted than the vowel of {{sc2|THOUGHT}}.<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=235}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/o\u028ar/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| aw || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| aw || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awe || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awe || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| baud || board || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| baud || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bawd || board || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bawd || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bawn || borne || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| bawn || bourn; bourne; [[Bourne (disambiguation)|Bourne]] || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| caught || court || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| caw || core || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| daw || door || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| draw || drawer || {{IPA|\u02c8dr\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| flaw || floor || {{IPA|\u02c8fl\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| fought || fort || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| gaud || gored || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| haw || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| law || lore || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| maw || more || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| maw || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| paw || pore || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| paw || pour || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| raw || roar || {{IPA|\u02c8r\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| sauce || source || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| saw || soar || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| saw || sore || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| sawed || soared || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| sawed || sword || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| [[Sean]] || shorn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| shaw || shore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| [[Shawn (disambiguation)|Shawn]] || shorn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| taw || tore || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| yaw || yore || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| yaw || your || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n=== Calve\u2013carve merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>BATH</small> and <small>START</small>. It is found in some non-rhotic accents with [[Trap\u2013bath split|broad A]] in words like \"bath\". It is general in southern England (excluding rhotic speakers), Trinidad, the Bahamas, and the Southern hemisphere. It is a possibility for Welsh, Eastern New England, Jamaican, and Guyanese speakers.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| aunt || aren't || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0nt}}\n|-\n| calve || carve || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0v}}\n|-\n| cast || karst || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n| caste || karst || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n| fast || farced || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n<!-- \"parse\" tends to have {{IPA|/z/}} in RP and other BATH-broadening accents | pass || parse || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0s}} -->\n|-\n| passed || parsed || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n| past || parsed || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|}\n\n=== Paw\u2013poor merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>THOUGHT</small> and <small>CURE</small>. It is found in those non-rhotic accents containing the ''caught''\u2013''court'' merger that have also undergone the [[English-language vowel changes before historic /r/|pour\u2013poor merger]]. Wells lists it unequivocally only for the accent of Trinidad, but it is an option for non-rhotic speakers in England, Australia and New Zealand. Such speakers have a potential four-way merger ''taw''\u2013''tor''\u2013''tore''\u2013''tour''.<ref>Wells, p. 287</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u028a\u0259r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| gaud || gourd || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| haw || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| law || lure || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0}} || With [[yod-dropping]].\n|-\n| maw || moor || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| maw || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| paw || poor || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| raw || [[Ruhr]] || {{IPA|\u02c8r\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| shaw || sure || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| taw || tour || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| tawny || tourney || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0ni}}\n|-\n| yaw || your || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| yaw || you're || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n=== Batted\u2013battered merger ===\nThis merger is present in non-rhotic accents which have undergone the [[Phonological history of the high front vowels#Weak vowel merger|weak vowel merger]]. Such accents include Australian, New Zealand, most South African speech, and some non-rhotic English speech (e.g. Norfolk, Sheffield).\n\nA large number of homophonous pairs involve the syllabic ''-es'' and [[Agent noun|agentive]] ''-ers'' suffixes, such as ''merges-mergers'' and ''bleaches-bleachers''.  Because there are so many, they are excluded from the list of homophonous pairs below.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u026a\u0308/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| batted || battered || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| betted || bettered || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u025bt\u0259d}}\n|-\n| busted || bustard || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u028cst\u0259d}}\n|-\n| butches || butchers || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u028at\u0283\u0259z}}\n|-\n| butted || buttered || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u028ct\u0259d}}\n|-\n| charted || chartered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283\u0251\u02d0t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| chatted || chattered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| founded || foundered || {{IPA|\u02c8fa\u028and\u0259d}}\n|-\n| humid || humo(u)red || {{IPA|\u02c8hju\u02d0m\u0259d}}\n|-\n| masted || mastered || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u00e6st\u0259d, \u02c8m\u0251\u02d0st\u0259d}}\n|-\n| matted || mattered || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| modding || modern || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0252d\u0259n}} || With [[G-dropping]].\n|-\n| patted || pattered || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| patting || pattern || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u00e6t\u0259n}} || With [[G-dropping]].\n|-\n| satin || [[Saturn]] || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u00e6t\u0259n}}\n|-\n| scatted || scattered || {{IPA|\u02c8sk\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| splendid || splendo(u)red || {{IPA|\u02c8spl\u025bnd\u0259d}}\n|-\n| tatted || tattered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| tended || tendered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u025bnd\u0259d}}\n|-\n| territory || terror tree || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u025br\u0259tri\u02d0}} || With [[happy-tensing|''happy''-tensing]].\n|}\n\n=== Dough\u2013door merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>GOAT</small> and <small>FORCE</small>. It may be found in some southern U.S. non-rhotic speech, some speakers of [[African-American English]], some speakers in Guyana and some Welsh speech.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/o\u028a/}}\n! {{IPA|/o\u028ar/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| beau || boar || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| beau || bore || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bode || board || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| bode || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| bone || borne || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028an}}\n|-\n| bone || [[Bourne (disambiguation)|Bourne]] || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028an}}\n|-\n| bow || boar || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bow || bore || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bowed || board || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| bowed || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| chose || chores || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283o\u028az}}\n|-\n| coast || coursed || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028ast}}\n|-\n| coat || court || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028at}}\n|-\n| code || cored || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028ad}}\n|-\n| doe || door || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028a}}\n|-\n| does || doors || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028az}}\n|-\n| dough || door || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028a}}\n|-\n| doze || doors || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028az}}\n|-\n| floe || floor || {{IPA|\u02c8flo\u028a}}\n|-\n| flow || floor || {{IPA|\u02c8flo\u028a}}\n|-\n| foe || fore || {{IPA|\u02c8fo\u028a}}\n|-\n| foe || four || {{IPA|\u02c8fo\u028a}}\n|-\n| go || gore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261o\u028a}}\n|-\n| goad || gored || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261o\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoe || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028a}}\n|-\n| hoed || hoard || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoed || horde || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoed || whored || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoes || whores || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028az}}\n|-\n| hose || whores || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028az}}\n|-\n| lo || lore || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028a}}\n|-\n| load || lord; Lord || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| lode |