}} || With [[yod-dropping]].\n|-\n| Moe || moor || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| Moe || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mode || moored || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| mow || moor || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mow || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mowed || moored || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| Po || poor || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| [[Poe]] || poor || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| roe || Ruhr || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a}}\n|-\n| row || Ruhr || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a}}\n|-\n| shew || sure || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028a}}\n|-\n| show || sure || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028a}}\n|-\n| toad || toured || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| toe || tour || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028a}}\n|-\n| toed || toured || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| tow || tour || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028a}}\n|-\n| towed || toured || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| yo || your || {{IPA|\u02c8jo\u028a}}\n|-\n| yo || you're || {{IPA|\u02c8jo\u028a}}\n|}\n\n=== Often\u2013orphan merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>CLOTH</small> and <small>NORTH</small>. It may be present in old-fashioned Eastern New England accents,<ref>Wells, p. 524</ref> New York City speakers<ref>Wells (1982), p. 503</ref> and also in some speakers in Jamaica and Guyana. The merger was also until recently present in the dialects of [[southern England]], including [[Received Pronunciation]]\u2014specifically, the phonemic merger of the words ''often'' and ''orphan'' was a [[running gag]] in the [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] [[musical theatre|musical]], ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| boss || bourse || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| hoss<ref>Dialectal variant of \"horse\"</ref> || horse || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| moss || [[Morse (disambiguation)|Morse]] || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| off || [[Orff (disambiguation)|Orff]]; [[orfe]]; orf || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0f}}\n|-\n| often || orphan || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0f\u0259n}} || \"Often\" is pronounced with a sounded T by some speakers.\n|}\n\n=== God\u2013guard merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>LOT</small> and <small>START</small>. It may be present in non-rhotic accents that have undergone the [[father\u2013bother merger]]. These includes non-rhotic Rhode Island, New York City,<ref>Wells (1982), p. 504</ref> some Southern U.S.,<ref>Wells (1982), p. 544</ref> and some African-American accents.<ref>Wells (1982), p. 577</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0251r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| bob; Bob || barb; Barb || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0b}}\n|-\n| bock || bark || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| bocks || barks || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0ks}}\n|-\n| bocks || Berks || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0ks}}\n|-\n| bod || bard || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bod || barred || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| boff || barf || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0f}}\n|-\n| bot || [[Bart (disambiguation)|Bart]] || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| box || barks || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0ks}}\n|-\n| box || Berks || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0ks}}\n|-\n| clock || [[Clark]]; [[Clarke]] || {{IPA|\u02c8kl\u0251\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| clock || clerk || {{IPA|\u02c8kl\u0251\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| cob || carb || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0b}}\n|-\n| cod || card || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| collar || [[Carla]] || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0l\u0259}}\n|-\n| collie || Carlie || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0li}}\n|-\n| cop || carp || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0p}}\n|-\n| cot || cart || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| dock || dark || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| dollar || Darla || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0l\u0259}}\n|-\n| dolling || darling || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0l