veolar flapping]].\n|-\n| hub || herb || {{IPA|\u02c8(h)\u028cb}} || With or without [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| huck || [[Herc (disambiguation)|Herc]] || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u028ck}}\n|-\n| huck || irk || {{IPA|\u02c8\u028ck}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| huddle || hurdle || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u028cd\u0259l}}\n|-\n| hull || hurl || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u028cl}}\n|-\n| hum || herm || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u028cm}}\n|-\n| [[Hun]] || earn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u028cn}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| Hun || urn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u028cn}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| hush || [[Hirsch]] || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u028c\u0283}}\n|-\n| hut || hurt || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u028ct}}\n|-\n| love || lurve || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u028cv}}\n|-\n| luck || lurk || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u028ck}}\n|-\n| lucks || lurks || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u028cks}}\n|-\n| lunt || learnt || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u028cnt}}\n|-\n| luxe || lurks || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u028cks}}\n|-\n| much || merch || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028ct\u0283}}\n|-\n| muck || merc || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028ck}}\n|-\n| muck || mirk || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028ck}}\n|-\n| muck || murk || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028ck}}\n|-\n| muddle || myrtle || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028c\u027e\u0259l}} || With [[intervocalic alveolar flapping]].\n|-\n| mudder || murder || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028cd\u0259}}\n|-\n| mull || merl || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028cl}}\n|-\n| mutter || murder || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028c\u027e\u0259}} || With [[intervocalic alveolar flapping]].\n|-\n| mutton || Merton || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u028ct\u0259n}}\n|-\n| oven || Irving || {{IPA|\u02c8\u028cv\u0259n}} || With [[weak vowel merger]] and [[G-dropping]].\n|-\n| puck || perk || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u028ck}}\n|-\n| pudge || purge || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u028cd\u0292}}\n|-\n| pup || perp || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u028cp}}\n|-\n| pus || purse || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u028cs}}\n|-\n| pussy ''(pus)'' || Percy || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u028csi}}\n|-\n| putt || pert || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u028ct}}\n|-\n| scut || skirt || {{IPA|\u02c8sk\u028ct}}\n|-\n| shuck || shirk || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u028ck}}\n|-\n| spun || spurn || {{IPA|\u02c8sp\u028cn}}\n|-\n| stud || stirred || {{IPA|\u02c8st\u028cd}}\n|-\n| such || search || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u028ct\u0283}}\n|-\n| suck || cirque || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u028ck}}\n|-\n| suckle || circle || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u028ck\u0259l}}\n|-\n| suffer || surfer || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u028cf\u0259}}\n|-\n| sully || surly || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u028cli}}\n|-\n| [[Sutton (disambiguation)|Sutton]] || certain || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u028ct\u0259n}} || With [[weak vowel merger]].\n|-\n| thud || third || {{IPA|\u02c8\u03b8\u028cd}}\n|-\n| ton(ne) || tern || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028cn}}\n|-\n| ton(ne) || turn || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028cn}}\n|-\n| tough || turf || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028cf}}\n|-\n| tuck || Turk || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028ck}}\n|-\n| tucks || Turks || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028cks}}\n|-\n| [[Tuttle (surname)|Tuttle]] || turtle || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028ct\u0259l}}\n|-\n| tux || Turks || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u028cks}}\n|-\n| us || [[Erse (disambiguation)|Erse]] || {{IPA|\u02c8\u028cs}}\n|-\n| wont || weren't || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u028cnt}}\n|}\n\n== Up-gliding {{sc2|NURSE}} ==\n{{listen\n|filename=Coil\u2013curl merger.ogg\n|title=Up-gliding {{sc2|NURSE}}\n|description=Examples of the up-gliding {{sc2|NURSE}} in the words \"circus,\" \"thirty-five,\" and \"first,\" as spoken by native [[New York City English]] speaker [[Groucho Marx]].\n}}\nUp-gliding {{sc2|NURSE}} is a diphthongized vowel sound, {{IPA|[\u0259\u026a]}}, used as the pronunciation of the {{sc2|NURSE}} phoneme {{IPA|/\u025c/}}. This up-gliding variant historically occurred in some non-rhotic dialects of [[American English]] and is particularly associated with the early twentieth-century (but now extinct or moribund) dialects of [[New York City]], [[New Orleans]], and [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]],<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=259}}</ref> likely developing in the prior century. In fact, in speakers born before [[World War I]], this sound apparently predominated throughout [[Older Southern American English|older speech of the Southern United States]], ranging from \"South Carolina to Texas and north to eastern Arkansas and the southern edge of Kentucky.\"<ref>{{harvp|Thomas|2006|p=8}}</ref> This variant happened only before a consonant, so, for example, ''stir'' was never {{IPA|[st\u0259\u026a]}};<ref>{{harvp|Wells|1982|pp=508 ff}}</ref> rather ''stir'' would have been pronounced {{IPA|[st\u025c(r)]}}.\n\n=== Coil\u2013curl merger ===\nIn some cases, particularly in New York City, the {{sc2|NURSE}} sound gliding from a schwa upwards even led to a [[phonemic merger]] of the vowel classes associated with the [[General American]] phonemes {{IPA|/\u0254\u026a/}} as in {{sc2|CHOICE}} with the {{IPA|/\u025cr/}} of {{sc2|NURSE}}; thus, words like ''coil'' and ''curl'', as well as ''voice'' and ''verse'', were homophones. The merged vowel was typically a diphthong {{IPA|[\u0259\u026a]}}, with a mid central starting point, rather than the back rounded starting point of {{IPA|/\u0254\u026a/}} of {{sc2|CHOICE}} in most other accents of English. The merger is responsible for the \"Brooklynese\" stereotypes of ''bird'' sounding like ''boid'' and ''thirty-third'' sounding like ''toity-toid''. This merger is known for the word ''soitanly'', used often by the [[Three Stooges]] comedian [[Curly Howard]] as a variant of ''certainly'' in comedy [[short subject|shorts]] of the 1930s and 1940s. The songwriter [[Sam M. Lewis]], a native New Yorker, rhymed ''returning'' with ''joining'' in the lyrics of the English-language version of ''[[Gloomy Sunday]]''. Except for [[New Orleans English]],<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=260}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The YAT Language of New Orleans |last=Canatella |first=Ray |isbn=978-1-4620-3295-2 |publisher=iUniverse |year=2011 |pages=67, ... |quote=MOYCHANDIZE \u2013 Translation: Merchandise. \"Dat store seem to be selling nutin' but cheap moychandize\"}}</ref><ref name=Trawick>{{cite web |title=On the Hunt for the New Orleans Yat |last=Trawick-Smith |first=Ben |date=September 1, 2011 |work=Dialect Blog |url=http://dialectblog.com/2011/09/01/on-the-hunt-for-the-new-orleans-yat |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref>  this merger did not occur in the South, despite up-gliding {{sc2|NURSE}} existing in some older Southern accents; instead, a distinction between the two phonemes was maintained due to a down-gliding {{sc2|CHOICE}} sound: something like {{IPA|[\u0254\u025b]}}.\n\nIn 1966, according to a survey that was done by [[William Labov]] in New York City, 100% of the people over 60 used {{IPA|[\u0259\u026a]}} for bird. With each younger age group, however, the percentage got progressively lower: 59% of 50- to 59-year-olds, 33% of 40- to 49-year-olds, 24% of 20- to 39-year-olds, and finally, only 4% of people 8\u201319 years old used {{IPA|[\u0259\u026a]}}. Nearly all native New Yorkers born since 1950, even those whose speech is otherwise [[non-rhotic]], now pronounce ''bird'' as {{IPA|[b\u025dd]}}.<ref>{{harvp|Labov|1966}}</ref>  However, Labov reports this vowel to be slightly raised compared to other dialects.<ref>{{harvp|Labov|1966|p=216}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u026a/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u025c\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| adjoin || adjourn || {{IPA|\u0259\u02c8d\u0292\u0259\u026an}}\n|-\n| boil || burl || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| [[Boyd (disambiguation)|Boyd]] || bird || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0259\u026ad}}\n|-\n| [[Boyle (disambiguation)|Boyle]] || burl || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| coil || curl || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| coin || kern || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0259\u026an}}\n|-\n| coitus || [[Curtis]] || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0259\u026at\u0259s}} || With [[weak vowel merger]].\n|-\n| foil || furl || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| goitre; goiter || girder || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0259\u026a\u027e\u0259r}} || With [[intervocalic alveolar flapping]].\n|-\n| hoist || [[Hearst (disambiguation)|Hearst]] || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0259\u026ast}}\n|-\n| hoist || hurst; Hurst || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0259\u026ast}}\n|-\n| [[Hoyle]] || hurl || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| loin || learn || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0259\u026an}}\n|-\n| oil || earl || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| poil || pearl || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0259\u026al}}\n|-\n| poise || purrs || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0259\u026az}}\n|-\n| toyed || turd || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0259\u026ad}}\n|-\n| voice || verse || {{IPA|\u02c8v\u0259\u026as}}\n|-\n| [[Voight]] || vert || {{IPA|\u02c8v\u0259\u026at}}\n|}\n\n== Effect of non-rhotic dialects on orthography ==\nCertain words have spellings derived from non-rhotic dialects or renderings of foreign words through non-rhotic pronunciation. In rhotic dialects, [[spelling pronunciation]] has caused these words to be pronounced rhotically anyway. Examples include:\n* ''Er'', used in non-rhotic dialects to indicate a [[filled pause]], which most rhotic dialects would instead convey with ''uh'' or ''eh''.\n* The game [[Parcheesi]], from Indian [[Pachisi]].\n* British English slang words:\n** ''char'' for ''cha'' from the [[Mandarin Chinese]] pronunciation of {{zh|t=\u8336}} (= \"[[tea]]\" (the drink)){{Citation needed|reason=Please prove that 'char' isn't an adoption of the Gwoyeu Romatzyh spelling 'char' for \u8336 (where '-r' signals a syllable in the second tone the same way the acute accent of Pinyin 'ch\u00e1' does)|date=June 2018}}\n* In [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s books:\n** ''dorg'' instead of ''dawg'' for a [[drawl]]ed pronunciation of ''dog''.\n** Hindu god name [[Kamadeva|Kama]] misspelled as ''[[Karma]]'' (which is a concept in several Asian religions, not a god).\n** [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] {{wikt-lang|hi|\u0915\u093e\u0917\u093c\u091c\u093c}} / {{nq|{{wikt-lang|ur|\u06a9\u0627\u063a\u0630}}}} ''{{transl|ur|IAST|k\u0101ghaz}}'' (\"paper\") spelled as ''kargaz''.\n* The donkey [[Eeyore]] in [[A.A. Milne]]'s stories, whose name comes from the sound that donkeys make, commonly spelled ''hee-haw'' in American English.\n* ''Burma'' and ''Myanmar'' for [[Burmese language|Burmese]] {{IPA|[b\u0259m\u00e0]}} and {{IPA|[mj\u00e0mm\u00e0]}}.\n* Transliteration of Cantonese words and names, such as ''[[char siu]]'' ({{zh|t=\u53c9\u71d2|j=caa\u00b9 siu\u00b9}}) and [[Wong Kar-wai]] ({{zh|t=\u738b\u5bb6\u885e|j=Wong\u2074 Gaa1wai\u2076}})\n* The spelling of ''schoolmarm'' for ''school ma'am'', which Americans pronounce with the rhotic consonant. (It should, however, be pointed out that this particular term is not used in modern American English. It harkens back to a time when one teacher taught all grades in a rural district and was used to refer to that person in a polite formal way by the community.)\n\n== See also ==\n*[[English-language vowel changes before historic /r/]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|35em}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Cambridge History of the English Language, Volume VI: English in North America |last= Fisher |first= John Hurt |publisher = Cambridge University Press |year=2001 |editor-last= Algeo |editor-first = John |location= Cambridge | pages = 59\u201385 |chapter= British and American, Continuity and Divergence |quote=| ref = harv | isbn = 0-521-26479-0 |via=| authorlink=John Hurt Fisher }}\n*{{cite journal\n |last=Gick \n |first=Bryan \n |year=1999 \n |title=A gesture-based account of intrusive consonants in English \n |journal=Phonology \n |volume=16 \n |issue=1 \n |pages=29\u201354 \n |url=http://idiom.ucsd.edu/~bakovic/camba_files/phonoloblog/gick-intrusive-consonants-ph99.pdf \n |ref=harv \n |doi=10.1017/s0952675799003693 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412043850/http://idiom.ucsd.edu/~bakovic/camba_files/phonoloblog/gick-intrusive-consonants-ph99.pdf \n |archivedate=2013-04-12 \n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Kurath\n|first=H.\n|year=1964\n|title=A Phonology and Prosody of Modern English\n|place=Heidelberg\n|publisher=Carl Winter\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book | title=The Atlas of North American English | last2=Ash | first2=Sharon | last3=Boberg | first3=Charles | publisher=Mouton de Gruyter | year=2006 | isbn=3-11-016746-8| location=Berlin |pages=|quote=|via=|first1=William | last1=Labov | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book| title=The Cambridge History of the English Language, Volume III: 1476\u20131776 | last=Lass | first=Roger | publisher=Cambridge University Press | year=1999 | isbn=0-521-26476-6| editor-last=Lass | editor-first=Roger | location=Cambridge | pages=56\u2013186 | chapter=Phonology and Morphology |quote=|ref=harv |via=}}\n* {{Cite web|url=http://www.rehabmed.ualberta.ca/spa/phonology/features.htm|title=Phonological Features of African American Vernacular English (AAVE)|last=Pollock, Bailey, Berni, Fletcher, Hinton, Johnson, Roberts, & Weaver|first=|date=17 March 2001|publisher=|access-date=8 November 2016}}\n* {{cite book | title=Language in the British Isles | last=Trudgill | first=Peter | publisher=Cambridge University Press| year=1984 |isbn=| location=Cambridge |pages=|quote=|via=| authorlink=Peter Trudgill }}\n* {{cite book | title=Accents of English |last=Wells |first=J. C. | publisher=Cambridge University Press| year=1982 |isbn=| location=Cambridge |pages=|quote=|ref=harv|via=|authorlink=John C. Wells }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{History of English}}\n\n[[Category:English phonology]]\n[[Category:Rhotic consonants]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the quality of realization of English phoneme /r/ among dialects|Pronunciation of English /r/}}\n{{Short description|Whether \"r\" is pronounced in all positions; used to classify English dialects\n}}\n{{English phonology topics}}\n{{IPA notice}}\n'''Rhoticity in English''' is the pronunciation of the historical [[rhotic consonant]] {{IPA|/r/}} in all contexts by speakers of certain [[varieties of English]]. The presence or absence of rhoticity is one of the most prominent distinctions by which varieties of English can be classified. In '''rhotic varieties''', the historical English {{IPA|/r/}} sound is preserved in all pronunciation contexts. In '''non-rhotic varieties''', speakers no longer pronounce {{IPA|/r/}} in [[postvocalic]] environments\u2014that is, when it is immediately after a vowel and not followed by another vowel.<ref>Paul Skandera, Peter Burleigh, ''A Manual of English Phonetics and Phonology'', Gunter Narr Verlag, 2011, p. 60.</ref>{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}}  For example, a rhotic English speaker pronounces the words ''hard'' and ''butter'' as {{nowrap|{{IPA|/\u02c8h\u0251\u02d0rd/}}}} and {{nowrap|{{IPA|/\u02c8b\u028ct\u0259r/}}}}, whereas a non-rhotic speaker \"drops\" or \"deletes\" the {{IPA|/r/}} sound, pronouncing them as {{nowrap|{{IPA|/\u02c8h\u0251\u02d0d/}}}} and {{nowrap|{{IPA|/\u02c8b\u028ct\u0259/}}}}.{{efn|Other terms synonymous with \"non-rhotic\" include \"'''{{IPA|/r/}}-deleting'''\",{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}} \"'''''r''-dropping'''\",{{sfnp|Wells|1982|p=216}} \"'''''r''-vocalizing'''\", and \"'''''r''-less'''\";<ref name=\"Labov, Ash, and Boberg 2006: 47\"/> synonyms for \"rhotic\" include \"'''{{IPA|/r/}}-pronouncing'''\", \"'''''r''-constricting'''\", and \"'''''r''-ful'''\".{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}}<ref name=\"Labov, Ash, and Boberg 2006: 47\">Labov, Ash, and Boberg (2006): 47.</ref>}} When an ''r'' is at the end of a word but the next word begins with a vowel, as in the phrase \"tune''r a''mp\", most non-rhotic speakers will pronounce the {{IPA|/r/}} in that position (the [[linking R]]), since it is followed by a vowel in this case. Not all non-rhotic varieties use the linking R; for example, it is absent in non-rhotic varieties of [[Southern American English]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Gick|1999|p=31}}, citing {{Harvcoltxt|Kurath|1964}}</ref>\n\nThe rhotic varieties of English include the dialects of [[Scottish English|Scotland]], [[Irish English|Ireland]], and most of the [[American English|United States]] and [[Canadian English|Canada]]. The non-rhotic varieties include most of the dialects of modern [[England]], [[Welsh English|Wales]], [[Australian English|Australia]], [[New Zealand English|New Zealand]] and [[South African English|South Africa]]. In some varieties, such as those of some parts of the southern and northeastern United States,<ref name=\"auto\">Labov, Ash, and Boberg, 2006: pp. 47\u201348.</ref>{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}} rhoticity is a [[sociolinguistics|sociolinguistic]] [[variation (linguistics)|variable]]: postvocalic ''r'' is deleted depending on an array of social factors such as the speaker's age, [[social class]], [[ethnicity]] or the [[register (sociolinguistics)|degree of formality]] of the speech event.\n\nEvidence from written documents suggests that loss of postvocalic /r/ began sporadically during the mid-15th century, although these /r/-less spellings were uncommon and were restricted to private documents, especially ones written by women.{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}} In the mid-18th century, postvocalic /r/ was still pronounced in most environments, but by the 1740s to 1770s it was often deleted entirely, especially after [[Open vowel|low vowels]]. By the early 19th century, the southern British standard was fully transformed into a non-rhotic variety, though some variation persisted as late as the 1870s.{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=115}} This loss of postvocalic {{IPA|/r/}} in British English influenced southern and eastern American port cities with close connections to Britain, causing their upper-class pronunciation to become non-rhotic while the rest of the United States remained rhotic.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=76}} Non-rhotic pronunciation continued to influence American [[Prestige (sociolinguistics)|prestige speech]] until the 1860s, when the [[American Civil War]] began to shift America's centers of wealth and political power to rhotic areas with fewer cultural connections to the old colonial and British elites.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=77}} The advent of [[radio]] and [[television]] in the 20th century established a [[General American|national standard]] of American pronunciation that preserves historical {{IPA|/r/}}, with rhotic speech in particular becoming prestigious in the United States rapidly after the [[Second World War]].{{sfnp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|pp=5, 47}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n\n== History ==\n===England===\n[[File:RhoticEngland.png|200px|thumb|right|Red areas indicate where rural English accents were rhotic in the 1950s.<ref>Based on H. Orton, ''et al.'', ''[[Survey of English Dialects]]'' (1962\u201371).  Some areas with partial rhoticity, such as parts of the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], are not shaded on this map.</ref>]]\n[[File:RhoticEngland2.png|200px|thumb|right|Red areas are where English dialects of the late 20th century were rhotic.<ref>Based on P. Trudgill, ''The Dialects of England''.</ref>]]\n\nThe earliest traces of a loss of {{IPA|/r/}} in English appear in the early 15th century and occur before [[coronal consonant]]s, especially {{IPA|/s/}}, giving modern \"ass (buttocks)\" ([[Old English]] ''ears'', [[Middle English]] ''ers'' or ''ars''), and \"[[bass (fish)]]\" (OE ''b\u00e6rs'', ME ''bars'').{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}} A second phase of {{IPA|/r/}}-loss began during the 15th century, and was characterized by sporadic and lexically variable deletion, such as ''monyng'' \"morning\" and ''cadenall'' \"cardinal\".{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}} These {{IPA|/r/}}-less spellings appear throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, but are uncommon and are restricted to private documents, especially ones written by women.{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}}  No English authorities describe loss of {{IPA|/r/}} in the standard language prior to the mid-18th century, and many do not fully accept it until the 1790s.{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=114}}\n\nDuring the mid-17th century, a number of sources describe {{IPA|/r/}} as being weakened but still present.{{sfnp|Lass|1999|pp=114\u201315}}  The English playwright [[Ben Jonson]]'s ''English Grammar'', published posthumously in 1640, records that {{IPA|/r/}} was \"sounded firme in the beginning of words, and more liquid in the middle, and ends.\"{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=115}}  The next major documentation of the pronunciation of {{IPA|/r/}} appears a century later in 1740, when the British author of a primer for French students of English said: \"...in many words ''r'' before a consonant is greatly softened, almost mute, and slightly lengthens the preceding vowel\".<ref>Original French: \"''...dans plusieurs mots, l'''r'' devant une consonne est fort adouci, presque muet, & rend un peu longue la voyale qui le precede''\". {{harvp|Lass|1999|p=115}}.</ref> \n\nBy the 1770s, postvocalic {{IPA|/r/}}-less pronunciation was becoming common around London even in more formal, educated speech.  The English actor and linguist [[John Walker (lexicographer)|John Walker]] used the spelling ''ar'' to indicate the long vowel of ''aunt'' in his 1775 rhyming dictionary.<ref name=\"Labov, Ash, and Boberg 2006: 47\"/> In his influential ''Critical Pronouncing Dictionary and Expositor of the English Language'' (1791), Walker reported, with a strong tone of disapproval, that \"... the ''r'' in ''lard'', ''bard'', [...] is pronounced so much in the throat as to be little more than the middle or Italian ''a'', lengthened into ''baa'', ''baad''....\"{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=115}} Americans returning to England after the end of the [[American Revolutionary War]] in 1783 reported surprise at the significant changes in fashionable pronunciation.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=73}}  \n\nBy the early 19th century, the southern British standard was fully transformed into a non-rhotic variety, though it continued to be variable as late as the 1870s.{{sfnp|Lass|1999|p=115}} The extent of rhoticity across England in the mid-19th century is summarized as widespread in the book ''New Zealand English: its Origins and Evolution'':\n:[T]he only areas of England ... for which we have ''no'' evidence of rhoticity in the mid-nineteenth century lie in two separate corridors.  The first runs south from the North Riding of Yorkshire through the Vale of York into north and central Lincolnshire, nearly all of Nottinghamshire, and adjacent areas of Derbyshire, Leicestershire, and Staffordshire.  The second includes all of Norfolk, western Suffolk and Essex, eastern Cambridgeshire and Hertfordshire, Middlesex, and northern Surrey and Kent.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Gordon\n|editor1-first=Elizabeth\n|editor2-last=Campbell\n|editor2-first=Lyle\n|editor3-last=Hay\n|editor3-first=Jennifer\n|editor4-last=Maclagan\n|editor4-first=Margaret\n|editor5-last=Sudbury\n|editor6-first=Andrea\n|editor6-last=Trudgill\n|editor5-first=Peter\n|year=2004\n|title=New Zealand English: Its Origins and Evolution\n|publication-place=Cambridge\n|publisher=Cambridge University Press\n|page=174}}</ref> \n\nRecordings of prisoners of war from the [[First World War]] in the Berliner Lautarchiv show rhoticity from dialects where the feature has since died out (e.g. [[Wakefield]] in Yorkshire).<ref>{{cite article|last=Aveyard|first=Edward|title=Berliner Lautarchiv: the Wakefield Sample|journal=Transactions of the Yorkshire Dialect Society|year=2019|pages=1-5}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nThe loss of postvocalic {{IPA|/r/}} in the British prestige standard in the late 18th and early 19th centuries influenced American port cities with close connections to Britain, and caused upper-class pronunciation in many eastern and southern port cities such as [[New York City]], [[Boston]], [[Alexandria, Virginia|Alexandria]], [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], and [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] to become non-rhotic.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=76}}  Like regional dialects in England, the accents of other areas in America remained rhotic in a display of linguistic \"lag\" that preserved the original pronunciation of {{IPA|/r/}}.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=76}}  \n\nNon-rhotic pronunciation continued to influence American prestige speech until the 1860s, when the [[American Civil War]] shifted America's centers of wealth and political power to areas with fewer cultural connections to the British elite.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=77}}  This trend increased after the [[Second World War]].{{sfnp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|pp=5, 47}} This largely removed the prestige associated with non-rhotic pronunciation in America, so that when the advent of radio and television in the 20th century established a national standard of American pronunciation, it became a rhotic variety that preserves historical {{IPA|/r/}}.{{sfnp|Fisher|2001|p=77}}\n\n== Modern pronunciation ==\nIn most non-rhotic accents, if a word ending in written \"r\" is followed immediately by a word beginning with a vowel, the {{IPA|/r/}} is pronounced\u2014as in ''water ice''. This phenomenon is referred to as \"[[Linking and intrusive R|linking R]]\". Many non-rhotic speakers also insert an [[epenthesis|epenthetic]] {{IPA|/r/}} between vowels when the first vowel is one that can occur before syllable-final ''r'' (''drawring'' for ''drawing''). This so-called \"[[Linking and intrusive R|intrusive R]]\" has been stigmatized, but nowadays many speakers of [[Received Pronunciation]] (RP) frequently \"intrude\" an [[epenthetic]] {{IPA|/r/}} at word boundaries, especially where one or both vowels is [[schwa]]; for example ''the idea of it'' becomes ''the idea-r-of it'', ''Australia and New Zealand'' becomes ''Australia-r-and New Zealand'', the formerly well-known [[India Office|''India-r-Office'']] and \"Laura Norder\" (Law and Order). The typical alternative used by RP speakers (and some rhotic speakers as well) is to insert a [[glottal stop]] where an intrusive R would otherwise be placed.<ref>Wells, ''Accents of English'', 1:224-225.</ref><ref>{{citation|last=Gimson|first=Alfred Charles|editor-last=Cruttenden|editor-first=Alan|year=2014|title=Gimson's Pronunciation of English|pages=119\u2013120|publisher=Routledge|edition=8th|isbn=978-1-4441-8309-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M2nMAgAAQBAJ\n}}</ref>\n\nFor non-rhotic speakers, what was historically a vowel plus {{IPA|/r/}} is now usually realized as a [[long vowel]]. This is called [[compensatory lengthening]], lengthening that occurs after the elision of a sound. So in RP and many other non-rhotic accents ''card, fern, born'' are pronounced {{IPA|[k\u0251\u02d0d]}}, {{IPA|[f\u025c\u02d0n]}}, {{IPA|[b\u0254\u02d0n]}} or similar (actual pronunciations vary from accent to accent). This length may be retained in phrases, so while ''car'' pronounced in isolation is {{IPA|[k\u0251\u02d0]}}, ''car owner'' is {{IPA|[\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0r\u0259\u028an\u0259]}}. But a final schwa usually remains short, so ''water'' in isolation is {{IPA|[w\u0254\u02d0t\u0259]}}. In RP and similar accents the vowels {{IPA|/i\u02d0/}} and {{IPA|/u\u02d0/}} (or {{IPA|/\u028a/}}), when followed by ''r'', become [[diphthong]]s ending in schwa, so ''near'' is {{IPA|[n\u026a\u0259]}} and ''poor'' is {{IPA|[p\u028a\u0259]}}, though these have other realizations as well, including monophthongal ones; once again, the pronunciations vary from accent to accent. The same happens to [[diphthong]]s followed by R, though these may be considered to end in {{IPA|/\u0259r/}} in rhotic speech, and it is the {{IPA|/\u0259r/}} that reduces to schwa as usual in non-rhotic speech: ''tire'' said in isolation is {{IPA|[ta\u026a\u0259]}} and ''sour'' is {{IPA|[sa\u028a\u0259]}}.<ref>''[[Shorter Oxford English Dictionary]]''</ref>  For some speakers, some long vowels alternate with a [[diphthong]] ending in schwa, so ''wear'' may be {{IPA|[w\u025b\u0259]}} but ''wearing''  {{IPA|[\u02c8w\u025b\u02d0\u0279\u026a\u014b]}}.\n\nEven General American speakers commonly drop the {{IPA|/r/}} in non-final unstressed syllables when another syllable in the same word also contains {{IPA|/r/}}; this may be referred to as ''R-dissimilation''. Examples include the dropping of the first {{IPA|/r/}} in the words ''surprise'', ''governor'' and ''caterpillar''. In more careful speech, however, the {{IPA|/r/}} sounds are all retained.<ref>Wells, ''Accents of English'', p. 490.</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\n[[File:Final er in Farmer English dialects.PNG|thumb|\nFinal post-vocalic '''{{IPA|/r/}}''' in ''farmer'' in English rural dialects of the 1950s<ref>Wakelyn, Martin: \"Rural dialects in England\", in: Trudgill, Peter (1984): Language in the British Isles, p.77</ref>\n----\n{{legend|lightgreen|{{IPA|[\u0259]}} (non-rhotic)}}\n{{legend|yellow|{{IPA|[\u0259\u02b4]}} ([[alveolar consonant|alveolar]])}}\n{{legend|orange|{{IPA|[\u0259\u02b5]}} ([[retroflex consonant|retroflex]])}}\n{{legend|deeppink|{{IPA|[\u0259\u02b5\u02d0]}} ([[retroflex consonant|retroflex]] & [[length (phonetics)|long]])}}\n{{legend|cyan|{{IPA|[\u0259\u02b6]}} ([[guttural R|uvular]])}}\n{{legend|magenta|{{IPA|[\u0254\u02b6]}} ([[back vowel|back]] & [[roundedness|rounded]])}}\n]]\nRhotic accents include most varieties of [[Scottish English]], [[Hiberno-English|Irish or Hiberno-English]], [[North American English]], [[English in Barbados|Barbadian English]], [[Indian English]],<ref name=\"wells\">{{cite book |isbn=0-521-28541-0 |first=J. C. |last=Wells |authorlink=J. C. Wells |title=Accents of English 3: Beyond the British Isles |location = Cambridge, UK |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1982 |page=629}}</ref> and [[Pakistani English]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Pakistani English: phonology|date=2008-01-18|url=http://www.reference-global.com/doi/abs/10.1515/9783110208429.1.244|work=Africa, South and Southeast Asia|editor-last=Mesthrie|editor-first=Rajend|url-status=dead|publisher=Mouton de Gruyter|doi=10.1515/9783110208429.1.244|isbn=9783110208429|access-date=2019-04-16|editor2-last=Kortmann|editor2-first=Bernd|editor3-last=Schneider|editor3-first=Edgar W.}}</ref>\n\nNon-rhotic accents include most varieties of [[English language in England|English English]], [[Welsh English]], [[New Zealand English]], [[Australian English]], [[South African English]] and [[Trinidadian and Tobagonian English]].\n\nSemi-rhotic accents have also been studied, such as [[Jamaican English]], in which ''r'' is pronounced (as in even non-rhotic accents) before vowels, but also in stressed monosyllables or stressed syllables at the ends of words (e.g. in \"car\" or \"dare\"); however, it is not pronounced at the end of unstressed syllables (e.g. in \"water\") or before consonants (e.g. \"market\").<ref>Wells, ''Accents of English'', pp. 76, 221</ref>\n\n[[variation (linguistics)|Variably]] rhotic accents are also widely documented, in which deletion of ''r'' (when not before vowels) is optional; in these dialects the probability of deleting ''r'' may vary depending on social, stylistic, and contextual factors. Variably rhotic accents comprise much of [[Caribbean English]], for example, as spoken in [[Tobago]], Guyana, Antigua and Barbuda, and the Bahamas.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schneider|first=Edgar|title=Varieties of English: The Americas and the Caribbean|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2008|page=396|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bGjixKTt9JcC&q=%22variably+rhotic%22}}</ref> They also include current-day [[New York City English]],<ref name=\"McClear\">{{cite news |url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/why_the_classic_noo_yawk_accent_yy2b2mA08qsg4sRxUDLVOL |title=Why the classic Noo Yawk accent is fading away |author= McClear, Sheila |work=New York Post |date=2 June 2010 |access-date=13 April 2013}}</ref> [[New York Latino English]], and some [[Boston English]], as well as some varieties of [[Scottish English]].<ref name=\"stuartsmith\" />\n\nNon-rhotic accents in the Americas include those of the rest of the Caribbean and Belize.\n\n=== England ===\nThough most [[English language in England|English varieties in England]] are non-rhotic today, stemming from a trend toward this in southeastern England accelerating in the very late 18th century onwards, rhotic accents are still found in the [[West Country dialects|West Country]] (south and west of a line from near [[Shrewsbury]] to around [[Portsmouth]]), the [[Corby]] area, some of [[Lancashire dialect|Lancashire]] (north and west of the centre of [[Manchester]]), some parts of [[Yorkshire dialect|Yorkshire]] and [[Lincolnshire]], and in the areas that border Scotland. The prestige form, however, exerts a steady pressure toward non-rhoticity. Thus the urban speech of Bristol or Southampton is more accurately described as variably rhotic, the degree of rhoticity being reduced as one moves up the class and formality scales.<ref name=\"Trudgill\">{{cite book |isbn=978-0-521-28409-7 |first=Peter |last=Trudgill |authorlink=Peter Trudgill |title=Language in the British Isles |location = Cambridge, UK |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1984}}</ref>\n\n=== Scotland ===\nMost Scottish accents are rhotic, but non-rhotic speech has been reported in Edinburgh since the 1970s and Glasgow since the 1980s.<ref name=\"stuartsmith\">{{cite book |last=Stuart-Smith|first=Jane|editor-last1=Foulkes |editor-first1=Paul |editor-last2=Docherty |editor-first2=Gerard |title=Urban Voices |publisher=Arnold |date=1999 |page=210|chapter=Glasgow: accent and voice quality |isbn=0-340-70608-2}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n[[File:Non-RhoticityUSA.png|thumb|left|Red dots show major U.S. cities where the 2006 ''[[Atlas of North American English]]'' found 50% or higher ''non''-rhotic speech in at least one white speaker within their data sample.{{sfnp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|pp=5, 47}} (Non-rhotic speech may be found in speakers of [[AAVE|African-American English]] throughout the country.)]]\n[[American English]] is predominantly rhotic today, but at the end of the 1800s non-rhotic accents were common throughout much of the coastal Eastern and Southern U.S., including along the [[Gulf Coast of the United States|Gulf Coast]]. In fact, non-rhotic accents were established in all major U.S. cities along the Atlantic coast except for the [[Delaware Valley]] area centered around [[Philadelphia]] and [[Baltimore]]. During the early to mid-1900s (presumably correlated with the Second World War),{{sfnp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|pp=5, 47}} rhotic accents began to gain social prestige even in the these traditionally non-rhotic areas. Thus, non-rhotic accents are increasingly perceived by Americans as sounding foreign or less educated, while rhotic accents are increasingly seen as sounding more \"[[General American]]\".<ref>{{cite book | title=English Historical Sociolinguistics | author=Milla, Robert McColl | pages=25\u201326 | publisher=Edinburgh University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-7486-4181-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdJGzHtdEVgC}}</ref>\n\nToday, non-rhoticity in the [[Southern American English|American South]] is found primarily among older speakers, and only in some areas such as central and southern [[Alabama]]; [[Savannah, Georgia]]; and [[Norfolk, Virginia]],<ref name=\"auto\"/> as well as in the ''[[New Orleans English|Yat]]'' accent of [[New Orleans]]. The local dialects of eastern [[New England]], especially [[Boston accent|Boston, Massachusetts]], extending into the states of [[Maine]] and (less so) [[New Hampshire]], show some non-rhoticity, as well as the traditional [[Rhode Island]] dialect; however, this feature has been receding in the recent generations. The [[New York City English|New York City dialect]] is traditionally non-rhotic, though [[William Labov]] more precisely classifies its current form as variably rhotic,<ref>{{cite book|title=Investigations in Sociohistorical Linguistics|year=2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|last=Trudgill|first=Peter|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBWAgZ2Isb0C&q=%22variability+can+be%22}}</ref> with many of its sub-varieties now fully rhotic, such as in [[New Jersey English|northeastern New Jersey]].\n\n[[African-American Vernacular English]] (AAVE) is largely non-rhotic, and in some non-rhotic Southern and AAVE accents, there is no [[linking r|linking ''r'']], that is, {{IPA|/r/}} at the end of a word is deleted even when the following word starts with a vowel, so that \"Mister Adams\" is pronounced {{IPA|[m\u026ast\u0259(\u0294)\u02c8\u00e6d\u0259mz]}}.<ref>Gick, Bryan.  1999.  [http://idiom.ucsd.edu/~bakovic/camba_files/phonoloblog/gick-intrusive-consonants-ph99.pdf A gesture-based account of intrusive consonants in English] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412043850/http://idiom.ucsd.edu/~bakovic/camba_files/phonoloblog/gick-intrusive-consonants-ph99.pdf |date=12 April 2013 }}.  ''Phonology'' '''16''': 1, pp. 29\u201354. ([[Portable Document Format|pdf]]).  Retrieved 12 November 2010.</ref> In a few such accents, intervocalic {{IPA|/r/}} is deleted before an [[Stress (linguistics)|unstressed]] [[syllable]] even within a word when the following syllable begins with a vowel. In such accents, pronunciations like {{IPA|[k\u00e6\u0259\u02c8la\u02d0n\u0259]}} for ''[[wikt:Carolina|Carolina]]'', or {{IPA|[b\u025b\u02d0\u02c8\u028cp]}} for \"bear up\" are heard.<ref>Harris 2006: pp. 2\u20135.</ref> This pronunciation also occurs in AAE.<ref>Pollock et al., 1998.</ref>  This also occurred for many older non-rhotic Southern speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlas.mouton-content.com/secure/generalmodules/varieties/unit0000/virtualsession/vslessons/thomas.pdf|title=Rural white Southern accents|last=Thomas|first=Erik R.|page=16|access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTypically, even non-rhotic modern varieties of American English do pronounce the {{IPA|/r/}} in {{IPA|/\u025cr/}} (as in \"bird,\" \"work,\" or \"perky\"), realizing it, as in most rhotic varieties, as {{IPAblink|\u025a|audio=y}} (an [[r-colored vowel|r-colored]] mid central vowel) or {{IPA|[\u0259\u0279]}} (a sequence of a mid central vowel and a postalveolar or retroflex approximant).\n\n=== Canada ===\n[[Canadian English]] is entirely rhotic except for small isolated areas in southwestern [[New Brunswick]], parts of [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]], and the [[Lunenburg English]] variety spoken in [[Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia|Lunenburg]] and [[Shelburne County, Nova Scotia|Shelburne Counties, Nova Scotia]], which may be non-rhotic or variably rhotic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Trudgill |first=Peter |title=Language Structure and Variation |year=2000 |publisher=Almqvist & Wiksell International |location=Stockholm |chapter=Sociohistorical linguistics and dialect survival: a note on another Nova Scotian enclave |editor=Magnus Leung|page=197}}</ref>\n\n=== Ireland ===\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2018}}\nThe prestige form of English spoken in Ireland is rhotic and most regional accents are rhotic although some regional accents, particularly in the area around counties [[County Louth|Louth]] and [[County Cavan|Cavan]] are notably non-rhotic and many non-prestige accents have touches of non-rhoticity.  In Dublin, the traditional local dialect is largely non-rhotic but the more modern varieties, referred to by Hickey as \"mainstream Dublin English\" and \"fashionable Dublin English\", are fully rhotic.  Hickey used this as an example of how English in Ireland does not follow prestige trends in England.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hickey|first=Raymond |editor-last1=Foulkes |editor-first1=Paul |editor-last2=Docherty |editor-first2=Gerard |title=Urban Voices |publisher=Arnold |date=1999 |page=272|chapter=Dublin English: current changes and their motivations  |isbn=0-340-70608-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Asia ===\nThe English spoken in Asia is predominantly rhotic. Many varieties of [[Indian English]] are rhotic owing to the underlying [[phonotactics]] of the native [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] and [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] languages<ref name=\"wells\" /> whilst some tend to be non-rhotic. In the case of the Philippines, this may be explained because the [[Philippine English|English]] that is spoken there is heavily influenced by the American dialect. In addition, many East Asians (in Mainland China, Japan, Korea, and Taiwan) who have a good command of English generally have rhotic accents because of the influence of [[American English]]. This excludes [[Hong Kong]], whose RP English dialect is a result of its almost 150-year-history as a British Crown colony (later British dependent territory). The lack of consonant /r/ in Cantonese also contributes to the phenomenon (although rhoticity started to exist due to the handover in 1997 and influence by US and East Asian entertainment industry). However, many older (and younger) speakers among South and East Asians speak non-rhotic.\n\nOther Asian regions with non-rhotic English are Malaysia, Singapore, and Brunei.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Mehmet|last1=Demirezen|year=2012|title= Which /r/ are you using as an English teacher? rhotic or non-rhotic?|url=https://pdf.sciencedirectassets.com/277811/1-s2.0-S1877042812X0017X/1-s2.0-S1877042812016710/main.pdf?X-Amz-Security-Token=IQoJb3JpZ2luX2VjEB0aCXVzLWVhc3QtMSJHMEUCIGLPfrckiP6JfY8%2F%2Fe2vzr1MwFPRyGZkn2yAaDs7%2BVAuAiEAl7RsBD22HGiOPAfx91Re2uEydfUT2pygLt7WCw89QaIq0AIIdhACGgwwNTkwMDM1NDY4NjUiDJw1CKFf0EJGm3uuTCqtAjtO2VgEetQnP%2FtEoBjaPqtP44HzjXLKSgwTexfhXpJRN4issG9aLCZJJou3RUivP8EBgd89TL98KnXnK3ljYnRavPHVrStcqKTdmA6K5hC806kkigumNf8D7v391mGbP75e6rFX0HM27wwCQt8sFzR5OguTqBHfG%2BaJRIOSqaMZdsn8UQCCzwjfGdyheIzJ18QDF4Sz2hWBsxHgXHLVqf%2BSpaMifPPsvudGGLDBra31EkpFI40P0er32pIoZVWFMrPLJXrqiRIjuwdzRoNwoKaCDo0fLzz5rA6JqEuZCjbDi5oL4xe2WO6p%2Fp9ljZwJv%2B%2B7p5ooHaeZwQvj6d0rktk%2Bg8EKqzorApQnxL5E%2BreUVtiGtGRRdlX6abz3fAen%2Fksz2VDxJTM%2B%2FvRJs70w8PHd7wU6zwJ3yHV7bRNCy6NT4wTIoxaTfn02PWfTiTGF20p67yqjnaaN52Rn5dsrTiDKoUs8D2C7PJl4wLM5p0lnqQPiYL%2FxhKCrMsDKNL9mOf6N6dWssH0kKJHLTP7TxANyV0DNqBVVuyCFeMxTbY6PQh4JU%2FoXXb2mE40TSh9bz6RVQnqkwWQ4WYnz1dHje%2FKdmUX8SAGoZ8%2FbIvOTuAL%2FNMQ3peuxGItuR9bdcxM4V9lHyocFFfvNAB5D65tnQFUQgjji9aRF14DWYF45L9Yxo5KSImAvW%2FX8v4zUjjmfLFpWgeSv11x%2FyxdiHUIJ5ezNvoqg07fXQatNMlwMjWBKAwFfZkbPplBC4AMD8ZsTDQOCuyMZhsCnjGxBFw6eR%2Fls1rgmfPdRBTJQhobAwLYyVa5bA0DBq6p7ctyHq8EFRiNcNhPbhaDJ9EJj88Py4OF2wQhRIQ%3D%3D&X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256&X-Amz-Date=20191216T133057Z&X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host&X-Amz-Expires=300&X-Amz-Credential=ASIAQ3PHCVTY7RXQQVVV%2F20191216%2Fus-east-1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request&X-Amz-Signature=bbb45797896ef9114665520f1348e5fb7b276910b62cb38400497407cfcd18ba&hash=f0c45400446ad742aa106eef3b931c6a56fbb631e1154a01b58fbe56aa55d78b&host=68042c943591013ac2b2430a89b270f6af2c76d8dfd086a07176afe7c76c2c61&pii=S1877042812016710&tid=spdf-7313d5f7-c9d2-4a04-a6df-b2dc0a1b6cc4&sid=a7c2684792d533422428cee211468d64af78gxrqa|work=Procedia - Social and Behavioral Sciences|volume=46|pages=2659\u20132663|publisher=Elsevier|doi=10.1016/j.sbspro.2012.05.542|ISSN=1877-0428|OCLC=931520939}}</ref> A typical Malaysian's English would be almost totally non-rhotic due to the nonexistence of rhotic endings in both languages of influence, whereas a more educated Malaysian's English may be non-rhotic due to Standard Malaysian English being based on RP ([[Received Pronunciation]]). The classical English spoken in Brunei is non-rhotic. But one current change that seems to be taking place is that Brunei English is becoming rhotic, partly influenced by American English and partly influenced by the rhoticity of Standard Malay, also influenced by languages of [[Indians in Brunei]] ([[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]) (rhoticity is also used by [[ethnic Chinese in Brunei|Chinese Bruneians]]), although English in neighboring Malaysia, Singapore, and Australia remains non-rhotic; rhoticity in Brunei English is equal to Philippine and Indian dialects of English and Scottish and Irish dialects. Non-rhoticity is mostly found in older generations, its phenomenon is almost similar to the status of American English, wherein non-rhoticity reduced greatly.<ref>Salbrina, S., & Deterding, D. (2010). Rhoticity in Brunei English. ''English World-Wide'', ''31'', 121\u2013137.</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Nur Raihan Mohamad|year=2017|title=Rhoticity in Brunei English : A diachronic approach|url=http://fass.ubd.edu.bn/SEA/volume17.html|work=Southeast Asia: A Multidisciplinary Journal|volume=17|pages=1-7}}</ref>\n\nA typical teenager's Southeast Asian English would be rhotic<ref name=\"gupta92\">{{cite journal|last1=Gupta|last2=Hiang|first1=Anthea F.|first2=Tan Chor|work=York Papers in Linguistics|date=January 1992|url= https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anthea_Gupta/publication/234677933_Post-Vocalic_r_in_Singapore_English/links/5884041ea6fdcc6b7910881e/Post-Vocalic-r-in-Singapore-English.pdf|volume=16|title=Post-Vocalic /r/ in Singapore English|pages=139\u2013152|ISSN=0307-3238|OCLC=2199758}}</ref>, mainly because of prominent influence by American English<ref name=\"gupta92\" />. Spoken English in Myanmar is non-rhotic{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}, but there are a number of English speakers with a rhotic or partially rhotic pronunciation. [[Sri Lankan English]] may be rhotic.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n=== Africa ===\nThe English spoken in most of Africa is based on RP and is generally non-rhotic. Pronunciation and variation in African English accents are largely affected by native African language influences, level of education and exposure to Western influences. The English accents spoken in the coastal areas of West Africa are primarily non-rhotic as are the underlying varieties of Niger-Congo languages spoken in that part of West Africa. Rhoticity may be present in English spoken in areas where rhotic Afro-Asiatic or Nilo Saharan languages are spoken across northern West Africa and in the Nilotic regions of East Africa. More modern trends show an increasing American influence on African English pronunciation particularly among younger urban affluent populations, where the American rhotic 'r' may be over-stressed in informal communication to create a pseudo-Americanised accent. By and large official spoken English used in post colonial African countries is non-rhotic. Standard [[Liberian English]] is also non-rhotic because liquids are lost at the end of words or before consonants.<ref>Brinton, Lauren and Leslie Arnovick. ''The English Language: A Linguistic History''. Oxford University Press: Canada, 2006</ref> South African English is mostly [[Rhotic and non-rhotic accents|non-rhotic]], especially Cultivated dialect based on RP, except for some Broad varieties spoken in the [[Cape Province]] (typically in -''er'' suffixes, as in ''writ'''er'''''). It appears that postvocalic {{IPA|/r/}} is entering the speech of younger people under the influence of [[American English]], and maybe an influence of Scottish dialect brought by Scottish settlers.{{sfnp|Bowerman|2004|p=940}}{{sfnp|Lass|2002|p=121}}\n\n=== Australia ===\nStandard [[Australian English]] is non-rhotic. A degree of rhoticity has been observed in a particular sublect of [[Australian Aboriginal English]] spoken on the coast of [[South Australia]], especially in speakers from the [[Point Pearce]] and [[Raukkan]] settlements. These speakers realise /r/ as [\u0279] in the preconsonantal [[postvocalic]] position \u2013 after a vowel but before another a consonant \u2013 but only within [[word stem|stems]]. For example: [bo\u02d0\u0279d] \"board\", [t\u0283\u025c\u0279t\u0283] \"church\", [p\u025c\u0279\u03b8] \"Perth\"; but [fl\u00e6\u02d0] \"flour\", [d\u0252kt\u0259] \"doctor\", [j\u026a\u0259z] \"years\". It has been speculated that this feature may derive from the fact that many of the first settlers in coastal South Australia \u2013 including [[Cornish English|Cornish]] tin-miners, [[Scottish English|Scottish]] missionaries, and [[American English|American]] whalers \u2013 spoke rhotic varieties.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Postvocalic R in an Australian English dialect|first=Peter|last=Sutton|year=1989|volume=9|issue=1|journal=Australian Journal of Linguistics}}</ref>\n\n=== New Zealand ===\nAlthough New Zealand English is predominantly non-rhotic, [[Southland Region|Southland]] and parts of [[Otago]] in the far south of New Zealand's [[South Island]] are rhotic from apparent Scottish influence.<ref>Clark, L., \"[https://www.nzherald.co.nz/technology/news/article.cfm?c_id=5&objectid=11763319 Southland dialect study to shed light on language evolution],\" ''[[New Zealand Herald]], 9 Dec 2016. Retrieved 19 March 2019.</ref> Older Southland speakers use {{IPA|/\u0279/}} variably after vowels, but today younger speakers use {{IPA|/\u0279/}} only with the {{sc2|NURSE}} vowel and occasionally with the {{sc2|LETT{{underline|ER}}}} vowel. Younger Southland speakers pronounce {{IPA|/\u0279/}} in ''third term'' {{IPA|/\u02cc\u03b8\u0275\u02d0\u0279d \u02c8t\u0275\u02d0\u0279m/}} (General NZE pronunciation: {{IPA|/\u02cc\u03b8\u0275\u02d0d \u02c8t\u0275\u02d0m/}}) but sometimes in ''farm cart'' {{IPA|/f\u0250\u02d0m k\u0250\u02d0t/}} (same as in General NZE).{{fix|text=stress needed|date=February 2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/speech-and-accent/page-5 |title=5. \u2013 Speech and accent \u2013 Te Ara Encyclopedia of New Zealand |website=Teara.govt.nz |date=2013-09-05 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> However, non-prevocalic {{IPA|/\u0279/}} among non-rhotic speakers is sometimes pronounced in a few words, including ''Ireland'' {{IPA|/\u02c8\u0251e\u0279l\u0259nd/}}, ''merely'' {{IPA|/\u02c8mi\u0259\u0279li/}}, ''err'' {{IPA|/\u0275\u02d0\u0279/}}, and the name of the letter R {{IPA|/\u0250\u02d0\u0279/}} (General NZE pronunciations: {{IPA|/\u02c8\u0251el\u0259nd, \u02c8mi\u0259li, \u0275\u02d0, \u0250\u02d0/}}).{{sfnp|Bauer|Warren|2004|p=594}} The M\u0101ori accent varies from the European-origin New Zealand accent; some [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] speakers are semi-rhotic like most white New Zealand speakers, although it is not clearly identified to any particular region or attributed to any defined [[language shift]]. The M\u0101ori language itself tends in most cases to use an r with an [[alveolar tap]] {{IPA|[\u027e]}}, like Scottish dialect.<ref>Hogg, R.M., Blake, N.F., Burchfield, R., Lass, R., and Romaine, S., (eds.) (1992) ''The Cambridge history of the English language. (Volume 5)'' Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press. {{ISBN|9780521264785}} p. 387. Retrieved from [https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=419yI8SGcnEC&pg=PA387 Google Books].</ref>\n\n== Mergers characteristic of non-rhotic accents ==\nSome phonemic mergers are characteristic of non-rhotic accents. These usually include one item that historically contained an R (lost in the non-rhotic accent), and one that never did so. The section below lists mergers in order of approximately decreasing prevalence.\n\n=== {{sm|Comm<u>a</u>}}\u2013{{sm|lett<u>er</u>}} merger ===\nIn the terminology of [[John C. Wells]], this consists of the merger of the [[lexical set]]s <small>comm''a''</small> and <small>lett''er''</small>. It is found in all or nearly all non-rhotic accents,<ref name=\"Ref-1\">Wells (1982)</ref> and is even present in some accents that are in other respects rhotic, such as those of some speakers in Jamaica and the Bahamas.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n\nIn some accents, [[syllabification]] may interact with rhoticity, resulting in homophones where non-rhotic accents have centering diphthongs. Possibilities include ''Korea\u2013career'',<ref>Wells (1982), p. 225</ref> ''[[Shia Islam|Shi'a]]\u2013sheer'', and ''Maia\u2013mire'',<ref>{{cite book|title= Oxford rhyming dictionary|first= Clive|last= Upton|author2= Eben Upton|publisher= Oxford University Press|year= 2004|isbn= 0-19-280115-5|page= [https://archive.org/details/oxfordrhymingdic00upto/page/59 59]|url= https://archive.org/details/oxfordrhymingdic00upto/page/59}}</ref> while ''[[skua]]'' may be identical with the second syllable of ''obscure''.<ref>{{cite book|title= Oxford rhyming dictionary|first= Clive|last= Upton|author2= Eben Upton|publisher= Oxford University Press|year= 2004|isbn= 0-19-280115-5|page= [https://archive.org/details/oxfordrhymingdic00upto/page/60 60]|url= https://archive.org/details/oxfordrhymingdic00upto/page/60}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0259/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Ana (given name)|Ana]] || honor || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}} || With [[father-bother merger]].\n|-\n| [[Anna (given name)|Anna]] || honor || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}} || With father-bother merger and trap-bath split.\n|-\n| area || airier || {{IPA|\u02c8\u025b\u0259ri\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Basia]] || basher || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u00e6\u0283\u0259}} || Without trap-bath split.\n|-\n| CAPTCHA || capture || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u00e6pt\u0283\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Carla]] || collar || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0l\u0259}} || With [[god-guard merger]].\n|-\n| [[Magna Carta|Carta]] || Carter || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0t\u0259}}\n|-\n| cheetah || cheater || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283i\u02d0t\u0259}}\n|-\n| Darla || dollar || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251l\u0259}} || With [[god-guard merger]].\n|-\n| [[Dinah]] || diner || {{IPA|\u02c8da\u026an\u0259}}\n|-\n| coca || coker || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028ak\u0259}}\n|-\n| coda || coder || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028ad\u0259}}\n|-\n| cola || coaler || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028al\u0259}}\n|-\n| coma || comber || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028am\u0259}}\n|-\n| custody || custardy || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u028cst\u0259di}}\n|-\n| data || dater || {{IPA|\u02c8de\u026at\u0259}}\n|-\n| Dhaka || darker || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0k\u0259}} || With trap\u2013bath split.\n|-\n| Easton || eastern || {{IPA|\u02c8i\u02d0st\u0259n}}\n|-\n| [[Federal Emergency Management Agency|FEMA]] || femur || {{IPA|\u02c8fi\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| Ghana || Garner || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| Helena || Eleanor || {{IPA|\u02c8\u025bl\u0259n\u0259}} || With [[h-dropping]]. Outside North America.\n|-\n| eta || eater || {{IPA|\u02c8i\u02d0t\u0259}}\n|-\n| eyen || iron || {{IPA|\u02c8a\u026a\u0259n}}\n|-\n| feta || fetter || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u025bt\u0259}}\n|-\n| formally || formerly || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0254\u02d0m\u0259li}}\n|-\n| geta || getter || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u025bt\u0259}}\n|-\n| ion || iron || {{IPA|\u02c8a\u026a\u0259n}}\n|-\n| karma || calmer || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| kava || carver || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0v\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Lena (name)|Lena]] || leaner || {{IPA|\u02c8li\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Lima]] || lemur || {{IPA|\u02c8li\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Lisa (given name)|Lisa]] || leaser || {{IPA|\u02c8li\u02d0s\u0259}}\n|-\n| Luna || lunar || {{IPA|\u02c8l(j)u\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| Maia || [[Meier]] || {{IPA|\u02c8ma\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| Maia || mire || {{IPA|\u02c8ma\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Maya peoples|Maya]] || [[Meier]] || {{IPA|\u02c8ma\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Maya peoples|Maya]] || mire || {{IPA|\u02c8ma\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| manna || manner || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u00e6n\u0259}}\n|-\n| manna || manor || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u00e6n\u0259}}\n|-\n| Marta || martyr || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0251\u02d0t\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Mia (given name)|Mia]] || mere || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| miner || myna(h); mina(h) || {{IPA|\u02c8ma\u026an\u0259}}\n|-\n| minor || myna(h); mina(h) || {{IPA|\u02c8ma\u026an\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Mona (name)|Mona]] || moaner || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028an\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Nia (given name)|Nia]] || near || {{IPA|\u02c8n\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| Palma || palmer; Palmer || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| panda || pander || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u00e6nd\u0259}}\n|-\n| parka || Parker || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0k\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Parma]] || palmer; Palmer || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Patton]] || pattern || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u00e6t\u0259n}}\n|-\n| [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] || peter; [[Peter (given name)|Peter]] || {{IPA|\u02c8pi\u02d0t\u0259}}\n|-\n| pharma || farmer || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Pia (given name)|Pia]] || peer || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| Pia || pier || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| pita || peter; [[Peter (given name)|Peter]] || {{IPA|\u02c8pi\u02d0t\u0259}} || \"pita\" may also be pronounced {{IPA|\u02c8p\u026at\u0259}} and therefore not merged\n|-\n| [[Rhoda]] || rotor || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a\u027e\u0259}} || With [[intervocalic alveolar flapping]].\n|-\n| Rita || reader || {{IPA|\u02c8ri\u02d0\u027e\u0259}} || With [[intervocalic alveolar flapping]].\n|-\n| Roma || roamer || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028am\u0259}}\n|-\n| rota || rotor || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028at\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Saba]] || sabre; saber || {{IPA|\u02c8se\u026ab\u0259}}\n|-\n| schema || schemer || {{IPA|\u02c8ski\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| Sia || sear || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| Sia || seer || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| seven || [[Severn]] || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u025bv\u0259n}}\n|-\n| soda || solder || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad\u0259}} || \"solder\" may also be pronounced {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0252d\u0259(r)}} and therefore not merged\n|-\n| soya || sawyer || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Stata]] || starter || {{IPA|\u02c8st\u0251\u02d0t\u0259}} || With trap\u2013bath split.\n|-\n| taiga || tiger || {{IPA|\u02c8ta\u026a\u0261\u0259}}\n|-\n| terra; Terra || terror || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u025br\u0259}}\n|-\n| Tia || tear (''weep'') || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| tuba || tuber || {{IPA|\u02c8t(j)u\u02d0b\u0259}}\n|-\n| tuna || tuner || {{IPA|\u02c8t(j)u\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| Vespa || vesper || {{IPA|\u02c8v\u025bsp\u0259}}\n|-\n| via || veer || {{IPA|\u02c8v\u026a\u0259}}\n|-\n| Wanda || wander || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u0252nd\u0259}}\n|-\n| Weston || western || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u025bst\u0259n}}\n|-\n| [[Wicca]] || wicker || {{IPA|\u02c8w\u026ak\u0259}}\n|}\n\n=== Father\u2013farther merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>PALM</small> and <small>START</small>. It is found in the speech of the great majority of non-rhotic speakers, including those of England, Wales, the United States, the Caribbean, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa. It may be absent in some non-rhotic speakers in the Bahamas.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| ah || are || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| ah || (h)our || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0}} || With [[monophthongization|smoothing]].\n|-\n| ah || R; ar || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| alms || arms || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0mz}}\n|-\n| alms || harms || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0mz}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| Ana || [[Arne (name)|Arne]] || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| balmy || barmy || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0251\u02d0mi}}\n|-\n| calmer || karma || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Chalmers (surname)|Chalmers]] || charmers || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283\u0251\u02d0m\u0259z}}\n|-\n| [[Dahmer (disambiguation)|Dahmer]] || dharma || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| Dhaka || darker || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0251\u02d0k\u0259}} || With trap\u2013bath split.\n|-\n| fa || far || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| father || farther || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0\u00f0\u0259}}\n|-\n| Ghana || Garner || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0251\u02d0n\u0259}}\n|-\n| [[Hamm]] || harm || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0251\u02d0m}} || With trap\u2013bath split.\n|-\n| [[Jahn]] || yarn || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0251\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| kava || carver || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0v\u0259}}\n|-\n| lava || larva || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0251\u02d0v\u0259}}\n|-\n| ma || mar || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| pa || par || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| Palma || [[Parma]] || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| palmer; Palmer || [[Parma]] || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0m\u0259}}\n|-\n| ska || scar || {{IPA|\u02c8sk\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| spa || spar || {{IPA|\u02c8sp\u0251\u02d0}}\n|-\n| Stata || starter || {{IPA|\u02c8st\u0251\u02d0t\u0259}} \n|}\n\n=== Pawn\u2013porn merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>THOUGHT</small> and <small>NORTH</small>. It is found in most of the same accents as the ''father\u2013farther'' merger described above, but is absent from the Bahamas and Guyana.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| alk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| auk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| aw || or || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awe || or || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| balk || bork || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| bawn || born || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| caulk || cork || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| cawed || chord || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| cawed || cord || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| draw || drawer || {{IPA|\u02c8dr\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| gnaw || nor || {{IPA|\u02c8n\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| hawk || orc || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0k}} || With [[H-dropping]].\n|-\n| laud || lord || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| lawed || lord || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| lawn || lorn || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| pawn || porn || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| sought || sort || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| stalk || stork || {{IPA|\u02c8st\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| talk || torque || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0k}}\n|-\n| taught || tort || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| taut || tort || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| taw || tor || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| thaw || [[Thor]] || {{IPA|\u02c8\u03b8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n=== Caught\u2013court merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>THOUGHT</small> and <small>FORCE</small>. It is found in those non-rhotic accents containing the ''pawn''\u2013''porn'' merger that have also undergone the [[horse\u2013hoarse merger]]. These include the accents of Southern England, Wales, non-rhotic New York City speakers, Trinidad and the Southern hemisphere. In such accents a three-way merger ''awe''-''or''-''ore/oar'' results.  However, Labov et al. suggest that, in New York City English, this merger is present in perception not production.  As in, although even locals perceive themselves using the same vowel in both cases, they tend to produce the {{sc2|FORCE}} higher and more retracted than the vowel of {{sc2|THOUGHT}}.<ref>{{Harvp|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|p=235}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/o\u028ar/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| aw || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| aw || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awe || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| awe || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| baud || board || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| baud || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bawd || board || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bawd || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| bawn || borne || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| bawn || bourn; bourne; [[Bourne (disambiguation)|Bourne]] || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| caught || court || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| caw || core || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| daw || door || {{IPA|\u02c8d\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| draw || drawer || {{IPA|\u02c8dr\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| flaw || floor || {{IPA|\u02c8fl\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| fought || fort || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0254\u02d0t}}\n|-\n| gaud || gored || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| haw || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| law || lore || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| maw || more || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| maw || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| paw || pore || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| paw || pour || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| raw || roar || {{IPA|\u02c8r\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| sauce || source || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| saw || soar || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| saw || sore || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| sawed || soared || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| sawed || sword || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| [[Sean]] || shorn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| shaw || shore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| [[Shawn (disambiguation)|Shawn]] || shorn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0n}}\n|-\n| taw || tore || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| yaw || yore || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| yaw || your || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n=== Calve\u2013carve merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>BATH</small> and <small>START</small>. It is found in some non-rhotic accents with [[Trap\u2013bath split|broad A]] in words like \"bath\". It is general in southern England (excluding rhotic speakers), Trinidad, the Bahamas, and the Southern hemisphere. It is a possibility for Welsh, Eastern New England, Jamaican, and Guyanese speakers.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| aunt || aren't || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0251\u02d0nt}}\n|-\n| calve || carve || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0v}}\n|-\n| cast || karst || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n| caste || karst || {{IPA|\u02c8k\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n| fast || farced || {{IPA|\u02c8f\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n<!-- \"parse\" tends to have {{IPA|/z/}} in RP and other BATH-broadening accents | pass || parse || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0s}} -->\n|-\n| passed || parsed || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|-\n| past || parsed || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0251\u02d0st}}\n|}\n\n=== Paw\u2013poor merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>THOUGHT</small> and <small>CURE</small>. It is found in those non-rhotic accents containing the ''caught''\u2013''court'' merger that have also undergone the [[English-language vowel changes before historic /r/|pour\u2013poor merger]]. Wells lists it unequivocally only for the accent of Trinidad, but it is an option for non-rhotic speakers in England, Australia and New Zealand. Such speakers have a potential four-way merger ''taw''\u2013''tor''\u2013''tore''\u2013''tour''.<ref>Wells, p. 287</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u028a\u0259r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| gaud || gourd || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261\u0254\u02d0d}}\n|-\n| haw || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| law || lure || {{IPA|\u02c8l\u0254\u02d0}} || With [[yod-dropping]].\n|-\n| maw || moor || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| maw || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| paw || poor || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| raw || [[Ruhr]] || {{IPA|\u02c8r\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| shaw || sure || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| taw || tour || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| tawny || tourney || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0254\u02d0ni}}\n|-\n| yaw || your || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|-\n| yaw || you're || {{IPA|\u02c8j\u0254\u02d0}}\n|}\n\n=== Batted\u2013battered merger ===\nThis merger is present in non-rhotic accents which have undergone the [[Phonological history of the high front vowels#Weak vowel merger|weak vowel merger]]. Such accents include Australian, New Zealand, most South African speech, and some non-rhotic English speech (e.g. Norfolk, Sheffield).\n\nA large number of homophonous pairs involve the syllabic ''-es'' and [[Agent noun|agentive]] ''-ers'' suffixes, such as ''merges-mergers'' and ''bleaches-bleachers''.  Because there are so many, they are excluded from the list of homophonous pairs below.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u026a\u0308/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0259r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| batted || battered || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| betted || bettered || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u025bt\u0259d}}\n|-\n| busted || bustard || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u028cst\u0259d}}\n|-\n| butches || butchers || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u028at\u0283\u0259z}}\n|-\n| butted || buttered || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u028ct\u0259d}}\n|-\n| charted || chartered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283\u0251\u02d0t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| chatted || chattered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| founded || foundered || {{IPA|\u02c8fa\u028and\u0259d}}\n|-\n| humid || humo(u)red || {{IPA|\u02c8hju\u02d0m\u0259d}}\n|-\n| masted || mastered || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u00e6st\u0259d, \u02c8m\u0251\u02d0st\u0259d}}\n|-\n| matted || mattered || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| modding || modern || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0252d\u0259n}} || With [[G-dropping]].\n|-\n| patted || pattered || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| patting || pattern || {{IPA|\u02c8p\u00e6t\u0259n}} || With [[G-dropping]].\n|-\n| satin || [[Saturn]] || {{IPA|\u02c8s\u00e6t\u0259n}}\n|-\n| scatted || scattered || {{IPA|\u02c8sk\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| splendid || splendo(u)red || {{IPA|\u02c8spl\u025bnd\u0259d}}\n|-\n| tatted || tattered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u00e6t\u0259d}}\n|-\n| tended || tendered || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u025bnd\u0259d}}\n|-\n| territory || terror tree || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u025br\u0259tri\u02d0}} || With [[happy-tensing|''happy''-tensing]].\n|}\n\n=== Dough\u2013door merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>GOAT</small> and <small>FORCE</small>. It may be found in some southern U.S. non-rhotic speech, some speakers of [[African-American English]], some speakers in Guyana and some Welsh speech.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/o\u028a/}}\n! {{IPA|/o\u028ar/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| beau || boar || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| beau || bore || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bode || board || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| bode || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| bone || borne || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028an}}\n|-\n| bone || [[Bourne (disambiguation)|Bourne]] || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028an}}\n|-\n| bow || boar || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bow || bore || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bowed || board || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| bowed || bored || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| chose || chores || {{IPA|\u02c8t\u0283o\u028az}}\n|-\n| coast || coursed || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028ast}}\n|-\n| coat || court || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028at}}\n|-\n| code || cored || {{IPA|\u02c8ko\u028ad}}\n|-\n| doe || door || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028a}}\n|-\n| does || doors || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028az}}\n|-\n| dough || door || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028a}}\n|-\n| doze || doors || {{IPA|\u02c8do\u028az}}\n|-\n| floe || floor || {{IPA|\u02c8flo\u028a}}\n|-\n| flow || floor || {{IPA|\u02c8flo\u028a}}\n|-\n| foe || fore || {{IPA|\u02c8fo\u028a}}\n|-\n| foe || four || {{IPA|\u02c8fo\u028a}}\n|-\n| go || gore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261o\u028a}}\n|-\n| goad || gored || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261o\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoe || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028a}}\n|-\n| hoed || hoard || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoed || horde || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoed || whored || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoes || whores || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028az}}\n|-\n| hose || whores || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028az}}\n|-\n| lo || lore || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028a}}\n|-\n| load || lord; Lord || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| lode || lord; Lord || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| low || lore || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028a}}\n|-\n| moan || mourn || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028an}}\n|-\n| Moe || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| Moe || more || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| Mona || mourner || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028an\u0259}}\n|-\n| mow || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mow || more || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mown || mourn || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028an}}\n|-\n| O || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028a}}\n|-\n| O || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028a}}\n|-\n| ode || oared || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028ad}}\n|-\n| oh || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028a}}\n|-\n| oh || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028a}}\n|-\n| owe || oar || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028a}}\n|-\n| owe || ore || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028a}}\n|-\n| owed || oared || {{IPA|\u02c8o\u028ad}}\n|-\n| Po || pore || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| Po || pour || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| [[Poe]] || pore || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| [[Poe]] || pour || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| poach || porch || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028at\u0283}}\n|-\n| poke || pork || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028ak}}\n|-\n| pose || pores || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028az}}\n|-\n| pose || pours || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028az}}\n|-\n| road || roared || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028ad}}\n|-\n| rode || roared || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028ad}}\n|-\n| roe || roar || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a}}\n|-\n| rose || roars || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028az}}\n|-\n| row || roar || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a}}\n|-\n| rowed || roared || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028ad}}\n|-\n| sew || soar || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028a}}\n|-\n| sew || sore || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028a}}\n|-\n| sewed || soared || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad}}\n|-\n| sewed || sored || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad}}\n|-\n| sewed || sword || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad}}\n|-\n| shone || shorn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028an}}\n|-\n| show || shore || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028a}}\n|-\n| shown || shorn || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028an}}\n|-\n| snow || snore || {{IPA|\u02c8sno\u028a}}\n|-\n| so || soar || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028a}}\n|-\n| so || sore || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028a}}\n|-\n| sow || soar || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028a}}\n|-\n| sow || sore || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028a}}\n|-\n| sowed || soared || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad}}\n|-\n| sowed || sored || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad}}\n|-\n| sowed || sword || {{IPA|\u02c8so\u028ad}}\n|-\n| stow || store || {{IPA|\u02c8sto\u028a}}\n|-\n| [[Thoth]] || tort || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028at}} || With [[th-stopping]].\n|-\n| toad || toward || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| toe || tore || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028a}}\n|-\n| toed || toward || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| tone || torn || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028an}}\n|-\n| tote || tort || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028at}}\n|-\n| tow || tore || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028a}}\n|-\n| towed || toward || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| woe || wore || {{IPA|\u02c8wo\u028a}}\n|-\n| whoa || wore || {{IPA|\u02c8wo\u028a}} || With [[wine\u2013whine merger]].\n|-\n| yo || yore || {{IPA|\u02c8jo\u028a}}\n|-\n| yo || your || {{IPA|\u02c8jo\u028a}}\n|}\n\n=== Show\u2013sure merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>GOAT</small> and <small>CURE</small>. It may be present in those speakers who have both the ''dough\u2013door'' merger described above, and also the [[English-language vowel changes before historic /r/|pour\u2013poor merger]]. These include some southern U.S. non-rhotic speakers, some speakers of [[African-American English]] and some speakers in Guyana.<ref name=\"Ref-1\" /> It can be seen in the term \"Fo Sho\", an imitation of \"for sure\".\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/o\u028a/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u028a\u0259r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| beau || Boer || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| beau || boor || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bow || Boer || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| bow || boor || {{IPA|\u02c8bo\u028a}}\n|-\n| goad || gourd || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0261o\u028ad}}\n|-\n| hoe || whore || {{IPA|\u02c8ho\u028a}}\n|-\n| lo || lure || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028a}} || With [[yod-dropping]].\n|-\n| low || lure || {{IPA|\u02c8lo\u028a}} || With [[yod-dropping]].\n|-\n| Moe || moor || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| Moe || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mode || moored || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| mow || moor || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mow || Moore || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028a}}\n|-\n| mowed || moored || {{IPA|\u02c8mo\u028ad}}\n|-\n| Po || poor || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| [[Poe]] || poor || {{IPA|\u02c8po\u028a}}\n|-\n| roe || Ruhr || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a}}\n|-\n| row || Ruhr || {{IPA|\u02c8ro\u028a}}\n|-\n| shew || sure || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028a}}\n|-\n| show || sure || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0283o\u028a}}\n|-\n| toad || toured || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| toe || tour || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028a}}\n|-\n| toed || toured || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| tow || tour || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028a}}\n|-\n| towed || toured || {{IPA|\u02c8to\u028ad}}\n|-\n| yo || your || {{IPA|\u02c8jo\u028a}}\n|-\n| yo || you're || {{IPA|\u02c8jo\u028a}}\n|}\n\n=== Often\u2013orphan merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>CLOTH</small> and <small>NORTH</small>. It may be present in old-fashioned Eastern New England accents,<ref>Wells, p. 524</ref> New York City speakers<ref>Wells (1982), p. 503</ref> and also in some speakers in Jamaica and Guyana. The merger was also until recently present in the dialects of [[southern England]], including [[Received Pronunciation]]\u2014specifically, the phonemic merger of the words ''often'' and ''orphan'' was a [[running gag]] in the [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] [[musical theatre|musical]], ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0254\u02d0r/}}\n! IPA\n! Notes\n|-\n| boss || bourse || {{IPA|\u02c8b\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| hoss<ref>Dialectal variant of \"horse\"</ref> || horse || {{IPA|\u02c8h\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| moss || [[Morse (disambiguation)|Morse]] || {{IPA|\u02c8m\u0254\u02d0s}}\n|-\n| off || [[Orff (disambiguation)|Orff]]; [[orfe]]; orf || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0f}}\n|-\n| often || orphan || {{IPA|\u02c8\u0254\u02d0f\u0259n}} || \"Often\" is pronounced with a sounded T by some speakers.\n|}\n\n=== God\u2013guard merger ===\nIn Wells' terminology, this consists of the merger of the lexical sets <small>LOT</small> and <small>START</small>. It may be present in non-rhotic accents that have undergone the [[father\u2013bother merger]]. These includes non-rhotic Rhode Island, New York City,<ref>Wells (1982), p. 504</ref> some Southern U.S.,<ref>Wells (1982), p. 544</ref> and some African-American accents.<ref>Wells (1982), p. 577</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | Homophonous pairs\n! {{IPA|/\u0251\u02d0/}}\n! {{IPA|/\u0251r/}}\n! IPA\n! Not